    <main>
        <h1>LeetCode 2833: Furthest Point From Origin (C++)</h1>

        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given a string moves of length n consisting only of characters 'L', 'R', and '_'. The string represents your movement on a number line starting from the origin 0. In the i<sup>th</sup> move, you can choose one of the following directions: move to the left if moves[i] = 'L' or moves[i] = '_', move to the right if moves[i] = 'R' or moves[i] = '_'. Return the distance from the origin of the furthest point you can get to after n moves.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: moves = "L_RL__R"<br/>
                Output: 3<br/>
                Explanation: The furthest we can reach from the origin 0 is point -3 through the following sequence of moves "LLRLLLR".<br/><br/>
                Input: moves = "_R__LL_"<br/>
                Output: 5<br/>
                Explanation: The furthest we can reach from the origin 0 is point -5 through the following sequence of moves "LRLLLLL".<br/><br/>
                Input: moves = "_______"<br/>
                Output: 7<br/>
                Explanation: The furthest we can reach from the origin 0 is point 7 through the following sequence of moves "RRRRRRR".
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int furthestDistanceFromOrigin(string moves) {
        int left = 0, right = 0, blank = 0;
        
        for (char move : moves) {
            if (move == 'L') {
                left++;
            } else if (move == 'R') {
                right++;
            } else {
                blank++;
            }
        }
        
        // Use all blanks to maximize distance in one direction
        return abs(left - right) + blank;
    }
};</code></pre>
